4:15:03 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/code/E11.9 200 in 217ms :: {"guidelines":[{"id":"0-II.A","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.A","title":"Locating a Code in the ICD-10-CM","content":"To select a code in the classification that corresponds to a diagnosis or reason for visit documented in a medical record, first locate the term in the Alphabetic Index, then verify the code in the Tabular List. Read and be guided by instructional notations that appear in both the Alphabetic Index and the Tabular List. It is essential to use both the Alphabetic Index and Tabular List when locating and assigning a code.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","locating codes","alphabetic index","tabular list"]},{"id":"0-II.B","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.B","title":"Level of Detail in Coding","content":"Diagnosis codes are to be used and reported at their highest number of characters available. A three-character code is to be used only if it is not further subdivided. A code is invalid if it has not been coded to the full number of characters required for that code, including the 7th character, if applicable.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","specificity","code detail","7th character"]},{"id":"0-II.C","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.C","title":"Code or Codes from A00.0 through T88.9, Z00-Z99.89","content":"The appropriate code or codes from A00.0 through T88.9, Z00-Z99.89 must be used to identify diagnoses, symptoms, conditions, problems, complaints or other reason(s) for the encounter/visit. Codes from A00.0 through T88.9 describe symptoms, signs, abnormal test results, or other reasons for the encounter. Z codes represent reasons for encounters and may be used in either the inpatient or outpatient setting.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","code selection","Z codes"]},{"id":"0-II.D","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.D","title":"Signs and Symptoms","content":"Codes that describe symptoms and signs, as opposed to diagnoses, are acceptable for reporting purposes when a related definitive diagnosis has not been established (confirmed) by the provider. The condition that is chiefly responsible for the outpatient encounter should be sequenced first. Integral signs/symptoms should not be coded separately unless instructed otherwise.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","signs","symptoms","sequencing"]},{"id":"0-II.E","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.E","title":"Conditions that are an Integral Part of a Disease Process","content":"Signs and symptoms that are associated routinely with a disease process should not be assigned as additional codes, unless otherwise instructed by the classification. Codes for signs/symptoms that are routinely associated with a disease (e.g., fever with bacterial pneumonia) should not be assigned separately.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","disease process","integral signs"]},{"id":"0-II.J","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.J","title":"Laterality","content":"Some ICD-10-CM codes indicate laterality, specifying whether the condition occurs on the left, right or is bilateral. If no bilateral code is provided and the condition is bilateral, assign separate codes for both the left and right side. If the side is not identified in the medical record, assign the code for the unspecified side. When a patient has a bilateral condition and each side is treated during separate encounters, assign the bilateral code for the condition still present on both sides.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","laterality","bilateral","left","right"]},{"id":"0-II.K","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.K","title":"Documentation by Clinicians Other than the Patient's Provider","content":"Code assignment is based on the documentation by the patient's provider (i.e., physician or other qualified healthcare practitioner legally accountable for establishing the patient's diagnosis). Codes may be assigned based on documentation by clinicians who are not the patient's provider only for codes for Body Mass Index (BMI), depth of non-pressure chronic ulcers, pressure ulcer stage, coma scale, and NIHSS codes.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","documentation","provider","BMI","clinician"]},{"id":"4-C4.a","chapter":4,"chapterTitle":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","section":"C4.a","title":"Diabetes Mellitus — Code Assignment","content":"The diabetes mellitus codes are combination codes that include the type of diabetes mellitus, the body system affected, and the complications affecting that body system. As many codes within a particular category as necessary should be used to describe all of the complications of the disease. They should be sequenced based on the reason for a particular encounter. Assign as many codes from categories E08-E13 as needed to identify all of the associated conditions that the patient has.","codeRangeStart":"E00","codeRangeEnd":"E89","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["diabetes","E08","E09","E10","E11","E13","combination codes","complications"]},{"id":"4-C4.a.1","chapter":4,"chapterTitle":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","section":"C4.a.1","title":"Type 1 vs Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus","content":"Type 1 diabetes mellitus is coded to category E10, Type 1 diabetes mellitus. Type 2 diabetes mellitus is coded to category E11, Type 2 diabetes mellitus. If the documentation does not specify the type, default to type 2. Age alone is not a determining factor. If a type 2 patient uses insulin, assign an additional code from category Z79.4, Long-term (current) use of insulin, or Z79.84, Long-term (current) use of oral hypoglycemic drugs. Do not assign Z79.4 if insulin is given as a temporary measure.","codeRangeStart":"E10","codeRangeEnd":"E11","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["diabetes","type 1","type 2","E10","E11","Z79.4","insulin","unspecified"]},{"id":"4-C4.a.3","chapter":4,"chapterTitle":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","section":"C4.a.3","title":"Secondary Diabetes Mellitus","content":"Codes under categories E08, Diabetes mellitus due to underlying condition, E09, Drug or chemical induced diabetes mellitus, and E13, Other specified diabetes mellitus, identify complications/manifestations associated with secondary diabetes mellitus. Secondary diabetes is always caused by another condition or event. The sequencing of the secondary diabetes codes is based on the reason for a particular encounter. Assign as many codes from categories E08, E09, and E13 as needed.","codeRangeStart":"E08","codeRangeEnd":"E13","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["diabetes","secondary diabetes","E08","E09","E13","drug-induced","sequencing"]},{"id":"0-IV.A","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Outpatient Coding and Reporting Guidelines","section":"IV.A","title":"Selection of First-Listed Condition (Outpatient)","content":"In the outpatient setting, the term 'first-listed diagnosis' is used in lieu of 'principal diagnosis.' The appropriate code(s) should be assigned to describe all diagnoses, symptoms, conditions, problems, or complaints treated or managed. The condition chiefly responsible for services provided is the first-listed diagnosis. Codes for signs and symptoms may be reported in addition to a related definitive diagnosis when the sign or symptom is not routinely associated with that diagnosis.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["outpatient","first-listed","principal diagnosis","sequencing","signs","symptoms"]},{"id":"0-II.A","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Inpatient Coding Guidelines","section":"II.A","title":"Principal Diagnosis — Inpatient Selection","content":"The condition established after study to be chiefly responsible for occasioning the admission of the patient to the hospital for care is the principal diagnosis. In the unusual instance when two or more diagnoses equally meet the criteria for principal diagnosis, any one may be selected as principal. If the original treatment plan is not carried out, the condition that caused the original admission should still be the principal diagnosis. Coding professionals should not hesitate to query the attending provider when documentation is ambiguous.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["inpatient","principal diagnosis","admission","sequencing","attending provider"]},{"id":"0-III","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Inpatient Coding Guidelines","section":"III","title":"Reporting of Additional Diagnoses","content":"For reporting purposes the definition for 'other diagnoses' is interpreted as additional conditions that affect patient care in terms of requiring clinical evaluation, therapeutic treatment, diagnostic procedures, extended length of hospital stay, or increased nursing care and/or monitoring. Diagnoses that relate to an earlier episode which have no bearing on the current hospital stay are to be excluded. UHDDS definitions apply to inpatient encounters in acute care, short-term, long term care and psychiatric hospital setting.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["additional diagnoses","inpatient","UHDDS","reporting","clinical evaluation"]},{"id":"0-HCPCS.GENERAL","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"HCPCS Level II Coding Guidelines","section":"HCPCS.GENERAL","title":"HCPCS Level II — Scope and Usage","content":"HCPCS Level II codes are alphanumeric codes (letter A-V followed by 4 digits) developed by CMS to describe items and services not covered by CPT codes. They cover ambulance services (A codes), durable medical equipment (E codes), procedures/professional services (G codes), covered drugs (J codes), temporary non-Medicare codes (K codes), dental (D codes), and other items. HCPCS Level II codes are required for billing to Medicare and Medicaid for items and services they describe. Always verify current-year active status before using.","codeRangeStart":"A0000","codeRangeEnd":"V5364","type":"HCPCS","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/healthcare-common-procedure-system","tags":["HCPCS","Level II","DME","ambulance","drugs","J codes","G codes","K codes"]},{"id":"0-HCPCS.E","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"HCPCS Level II Coding Guidelines","section":"HCPCS.E","title":"E-Codes — Durable Medical Equipment (DME)","content":"E codes describe durable medical equipment (DME) including mobility aids, respiratory equipment, and hospital beds. For Medicare DME billing, medical necessity must be established with appropriate ICD-10-CM diagnosis codes. DME must meet the criteria of being durable (withstand repeated use), used for medical purpose, not useful to a person in absence of illness, and used in the home. Items coded with E codes billed to Medicare DME MACs require detailed written orders (DWO) and documentation of medical necessity.","codeRangeStart":"E0100","codeRangeEnd":"E9999","type":"HCPCS","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/healthcare-common-procedure-system","tags":["HCPCS","E codes","DME","durable medical equipment","Medicare","medical necessity","E0100"]}],"nlmInfo":{"code":"E11.9","description":"Type 2 diabetes mellitus without complications","source":"ICD-10-CM"}}
4:15:16 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/stats 200 in 2ms :: {"totalGuidelines":46,"icdChapters":11,"cptGuidelines":3,"hcpcsGuidelines":3,"lastSync":"2026-03-11T16:15:16.216Z","chapters":[{"chapter":0,"title":"General Coding Guidelines","count":16},{"chapter":1,"title":"Certain Infectious and Parasitic Diseases","count":5},{"chapter":2,"title":"Neoplasms","count":3},{"chapter":4,"title":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","count":3},{"chapter":5,"title":"Mental, Behavioral and Neurodevelopmental Disorders","count":1},{"chapter":9,"title":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","count":5},{"chapter":10,"title":"Diseases of the Respiratory System","count":2},{"chapter":13,"title":"Diseases of the Musculoskeletal System and Connective Tissue","count":2},{"chapter":15,"title":"Pregnancy, Childbirth and the Puerperium","count":2},{"chapter":18,"title":"Symptoms, Signs and Abnormal Clinical and Laboratory Findings","count":1},{"chapter":19,"title":"Injury, Poisoning and Certain Other Consequences of External Causes","count":3},{"chapter":21,"title":"Factors Influencing Health Status and Contact with Health Services","count":3}]}
4:15:16 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/search 200 in 1ms :: {"data":[{"id":"9-C9.f","chapter":9,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","section":"C9.f","title":"Heart Failure — Combination Coding and Sequencing","content":"Heart failure is coded with combination codes from category I50. Diastolic and systolic heart failure are classified by type and acuity. If the documentation specifies both, assign the combination code. For heart failure due to hypertension, use the I11.- (hypertensive heart disease) or I13.- (hypertensive heart and CKD disease) category codes, plus the appropriate I50 code. Code the type of heart failure if documented. If combined systolic and diastolic, assign only the combination code and not separate codes.","codeRangeStart":"I50","codeRangeEnd":"I50","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["heart failure","I50","systolic","diastolic","I11","I13","hypertension","combination code"]},{"id":"9-C9.a","chapter":9,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","section":"C9.a","title":"Hypertension — Coding Rules","content":"A causal relationship is presumed between hypertension and heart involvement and between hypertension and chronic kidney disease (CKD), whether or not the provider has documented a link between these conditions. Unless the provider specifically documents that hypertension is not related to the CKD or the heart disease, code both together. Assign codes from categories I10-I16 (hypertension), with a code from I50 (heart failure) if applicable, and with a code from N18 (CKD) if applicable.","codeRangeStart":"I00","codeRangeEnd":"I99","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["hypertension","I10","CKD","heart failure","I50","N18","causal relationship"]}],"total":2,"page":1,"pageSize":5,"hasMore":false}
4:15:16 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/code/I10 200 in 184ms :: {"guidelines":[{"id":"0-II.A","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.A","title":"Locating a Code in the ICD-10-CM","content":"To select a code in the classification that corresponds to a diagnosis or reason for visit documented in a medical record, first locate the term in the Alphabetic Index, then verify the code in the Tabular List. Read and be guided by instructional notations that appear in both the Alphabetic Index and the Tabular List. It is essential to use both the Alphabetic Index and Tabular List when locating and assigning a code.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","locating codes","alphabetic index","tabular list"]},{"id":"0-II.B","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.B","title":"Level of Detail in Coding","content":"Diagnosis codes are to be used and reported at their highest number of characters available. A three-character code is to be used only if it is not further subdivided. A code is invalid if it has not been coded to the full number of characters required for that code, including the 7th character, if applicable.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","specificity","code detail","7th character"]},{"id":"0-II.C","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.C","title":"Code or Codes from A00.0 through T88.9, Z00-Z99.89","content":"The appropriate code or codes from A00.0 through T88.9, Z00-Z99.89 must be used to identify diagnoses, symptoms, conditions, problems, complaints or other reason(s) for the encounter/visit. Codes from A00.0 through T88.9 describe symptoms, signs, abnormal test results, or other reasons for the encounter. Z codes represent reasons for encounters and may be used in either the inpatient or outpatient setting.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","code selection","Z codes"]},{"id":"0-II.D","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.D","title":"Signs and Symptoms","content":"Codes that describe symptoms and signs, as opposed to diagnoses, are acceptable for reporting purposes when a related definitive diagnosis has not been established (confirmed) by the provider. The condition that is chiefly responsible for the outpatient encounter should be sequenced first. Integral signs/symptoms should not be coded separately unless instructed otherwise.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","signs","symptoms","sequencing"]},{"id":"0-II.E","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.E","title":"Conditions that are an Integral Part of a Disease Process","content":"Signs and symptoms that are associated routinely with a disease process should not be assigned as additional codes, unless otherwise instructed by the classification. Codes for signs/symptoms that are routinely associated with a disease (e.g., fever with bacterial pneumonia) should not be assigned separately.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","disease process","integral signs"]},{"id":"0-II.J","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.J","title":"Laterality","content":"Some ICD-10-CM codes indicate laterality, specifying whether the condition occurs on the left, right or is bilateral. If no bilateral code is provided and the condition is bilateral, assign separate codes for both the left and right side. If the side is not identified in the medical record, assign the code for the unspecified side. When a patient has a bilateral condition and each side is treated during separate encounters, assign the bilateral code for the condition still present on both sides.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","laterality","bilateral","left","right"]},{"id":"0-II.K","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"General Coding Guidelines","section":"II.K","title":"Documentation by Clinicians Other than the Patient's Provider","content":"Code assignment is based on the documentation by the patient's provider (i.e., physician or other qualified healthcare practitioner legally accountable for establishing the patient's diagnosis). Codes may be assigned based on documentation by clinicians who are not the patient's provider only for codes for Body Mass Index (BMI), depth of non-pressure chronic ulcers, pressure ulcer stage, coma scale, and NIHSS codes.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["general","documentation","provider","BMI","clinician"]},{"id":"9-C9.a","chapter":9,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","section":"C9.a","title":"Hypertension — Coding Rules","content":"A causal relationship is presumed between hypertension and heart involvement and between hypertension and chronic kidney disease (CKD), whether or not the provider has documented a link between these conditions. Unless the provider specifically documents that hypertension is not related to the CKD or the heart disease, code both together. Assign codes from categories I10-I16 (hypertension), with a code from I50 (heart failure) if applicable, and with a code from N18 (CKD) if applicable.","codeRangeStart":"I00","codeRangeEnd":"I99","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["hypertension","I10","CKD","heart failure","I50","N18","causal relationship"]},{"id":"0-IV.A","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Outpatient Coding and Reporting Guidelines","section":"IV.A","title":"Selection of First-Listed Condition (Outpatient)","content":"In the outpatient setting, the term 'first-listed diagnosis' is used in lieu of 'principal diagnosis.' The appropriate code(s) should be assigned to describe all diagnoses, symptoms, conditions, problems, or complaints treated or managed. The condition chiefly responsible for services provided is the first-listed diagnosis. Codes for signs and symptoms may be reported in addition to a related definitive diagnosis when the sign or symptom is not routinely associated with that diagnosis.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["outpatient","first-listed","principal diagnosis","sequencing","signs","symptoms"]},{"id":"0-II.A","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Inpatient Coding Guidelines","section":"II.A","title":"Principal Diagnosis — Inpatient Selection","content":"The condition established after study to be chiefly responsible for occasioning the admission of the patient to the hospital for care is the principal diagnosis. In the unusual instance when two or more diagnoses equally meet the criteria for principal diagnosis, any one may be selected as principal. If the original treatment plan is not carried out, the condition that caused the original admission should still be the principal diagnosis. Coding professionals should not hesitate to query the attending provider when documentation is ambiguous.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["inpatient","principal diagnosis","admission","sequencing","attending provider"]},{"id":"0-III","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"Inpatient Coding Guidelines","section":"III","title":"Reporting of Additional Diagnoses","content":"For reporting purposes the definition for 'other diagnoses' is interpreted as additional conditions that affect patient care in terms of requiring clinical evaluation, therapeutic treatment, diagnostic procedures, extended length of hospital stay, or increased nursing care and/or monitoring. Diagnoses that relate to an earlier episode which have no bearing on the current hospital stay are to be excluded. UHDDS definitions apply to inpatient encounters in acute care, short-term, long term care and psychiatric hospital setting.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"Z99","type":"General","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["additional diagnoses","inpatient","UHDDS","reporting","clinical evaluation"]},{"id":"0-HCPCS.GENERAL","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"HCPCS Level II Coding Guidelines","section":"HCPCS.GENERAL","title":"HCPCS Level II — Scope and Usage","content":"HCPCS Level II codes are alphanumeric codes (letter A-V followed by 4 digits) developed by CMS to describe items and services not covered by CPT codes. They cover ambulance services (A codes), durable medical equipment (E codes), procedures/professional services (G codes), covered drugs (J codes), temporary non-Medicare codes (K codes), dental (D codes), and other items. HCPCS Level II codes are required for billing to Medicare and Medicaid for items and services they describe. Always verify current-year active status before using.","codeRangeStart":"A0000","codeRangeEnd":"V5364","type":"HCPCS","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/healthcare-common-procedure-system","tags":["HCPCS","Level II","DME","ambulance","drugs","J codes","G codes","K codes"]}],"nlmInfo":{"code":"I10","description":"Essential (primary) hypertension","source":"ICD-10-CM"}}
4:15:16 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/type/CPT 200 in 1ms :: {"data":[{"id":"0-CPT.EM.2021","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"CPT Evaluation & Management (E/M) Guidelines","section":"CPT.EM.2021","title":"E/M 2021 Guidelines — Level Selection","content":"Effective January 1, 2021, the level of E/M office and outpatient visit is based on either: (1) Total time personally spent by the reporting clinician on the date of service; or (2) Medical decision making (MDM). The 1995 and 1997 examination guidelines no longer apply to outpatient E/M services. MDM is assessed in three elements: number and complexity of problems, amount and/or complexity of data reviewed, and risk of complications. All three elements of MDM must be considered when selecting the level based on MDM.","codeRangeStart":"99202","codeRangeEnd":"99499","type":"CPT","sourceUrl":"https://www.ama-assn.org/practice-management/cpt/changes-em-codes-2021","tags":["CPT","E/M","evaluation","management","99202","99213","MDM","time-based","2021 guidelines"]},{"id":"0-CPT.EM.NEW","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"CPT Evaluation & Management (E/M) Guidelines","section":"CPT.EM.NEW","title":"New vs Established Patient — E/M Classification","content":"A new patient is one who has not received any professional services from the physician/qualified health care professional or another physician/qualified health care professional of the exact same specialty and subspecialty who belongs to the same group practice, within the past 3 years. An established patient is one who has received professional services from the physician/qualified health care professional or another physician/qualified health care professional of the exact same specialty and subspecialty who belongs to the same group practice, within the past 3 years. New patient codes: 99202-99205. Established patient codes: 99211-99215.","codeRangeStart":"99202","codeRangeEnd":"99215","type":"CPT","sourceUrl":"https://www.ama-assn.org/practice-management/cpt/new-established-patient-guide","tags":["CPT","new patient","established patient","99202-99205","99211-99215","3-year rule"]},{"id":"0-CPT.PREV","chapter":0,"chapterTitle":"CPT Preventive Medicine Guidelines","section":"CPT.PREV","title":"Preventive Medicine Services — Age-Based Coding","content":"Preventive medicine service codes are based on the age of the patient. Codes 99381-99387 are for new patients; 99391-99397 are for established patients. The codes are further subdivided by age: infant (<1 year), early childhood (1-4), late childhood (5-11), adolescent (12-17), 18-39, 40-64, and 65+. When medical problems are addressed at the same encounter, report an additional E/M code with modifier -25. Annual wellness visits for Medicare patients are coded differently: G0402, G0438, G0439.","codeRangeStart":"99381","codeRangeEnd":"99397","type":"CPT","sourceUrl":"https://www.ama-assn.org/practice-management/cpt/preventive-medicine-services","tags":["preventive medicine","wellness","99381-99397","age-based","Medicare","G0438","G0439"]}],"total":3,"page":1,"pageSize":5,"hasMore":false}
